, āfui , āfŭtūrus , v. n., in its most general signif., to be away from, be absent.  In gen.  Absol. without designating the distance : : : : facile aerumnam ferre possum, si inde abest injuria, Caecil. ap. .— With reference to the distance in space or time; which is expressed either by a definite number, or, in gen., by the advs. multum, paulum longe, etc.: : : : : : :  .—With the simple abl. for ab:  Görenz; but, ab ejus villa, B. and K.; cf.: .— With inter: .—With prope, propius, proxime, to denote a short distance:  : : :  so  Caes. ap. —Hence the phrase: tantum abest, ut—ut, so far from —that, etc. : : ego vero istos tantum abest ut ornem, ut effici non possit, quin eos oderim, so far am I from—that,  sometimes etiam or quoque is added to the second clause, Lentul. ap.   more rarely contra, . Sometimes the second ut is left out:  on the contrary, once in Cic. with a third ut: tantum abest ut nostra miremur, ut usque eo difficiles ac morosi simus, ut nobis non satisfaciat ipse Demosthenes, Or. 29, 104. Hence,  To be away from any thing unpleasant, to be freed or free from: : : a reprehensione temeritatis, Planc. ap. . To be removed from a thing by will, inclination, etc.; to be disinclined to ' a consilio fugiendi, : : . toto aberant bello, . To be removed from a thing in regard to condition or quality, i. e. to be different from, to differ = abhorrere abest a tua virtute et fide, Brut. et Cass. ap. : istae  non longe absunt a scelere, : ,   42.—Since improvement, as well as deterioration, may constitute the ground of difference, so absum may, according to its connection, designate the one or the other:  : longissime Plancius a te afuit, i. e. valde, plurimis suffragiis, te vicit, was far from you in the number of votes, i. e. had the majority; v. Wunder ad Planc. proleg. p. 83 sq.; on the other hand, to be less, inferior: longe te a pulchris abesse sensisti, Cic. Fragm. ap. :  so . Not to be suitable, proper, or fit for a thing: : . To be wanting, = desum, Pac. ap. : : quaeris id quod habes;  cf.  and 1095.—After Cicero, constr. in this signif. with dat.: : .—So esp. in the poets:   .—Hence the phrase non multum , paulum, non procul, minimum, nihil abest, quin. not much, little, nothing is wanting that ; but not parum, since parum in good classical authors does not correspond in meaning with non multum, but with non satis :  and absol.: : : :  Abesse alicui or ab aliquo, to be wanting to any one, to be of no assistance or service to : : facile etiam absentibus nobis veritas se ipsa defendet, : . So also : et quo plus intererat, eo plus aberas a me, the more I needed your assistance, the more you neglected me, v. Wunder ad h. l.; cf. also  Cicero uses abesse to designate his banishment from Rome :  cf.: discessus. —Hence, absens, entis , P. a., absent .  In gen.:  so  : : :  :  :  al.—Sup.: .—Of things :  so, : : : : .— In partic.  In conversat. lang.  Praesens absens, in one's presence or absence: .— Absente nobis turbatumst, in our absence (so also:  Afran. ap. .— In polit. lang., not appearing in public canvassings as a competitor:  so  .— = mortuus, deceased,  , praef. § 8.— Ellipt.: absens in Lucanis, absent  in Lucania, i. e. absent and in Lucania,  so .

, cŭbui, cŭbĭtum, 3, v. n., to lay one's self down at a place; and hence, to lie somewhere.  In gen. :  .— In part.  To recline at table, in the manner in which the Romans reclined, after luxury and effeminacy had become prevalent. While they extended the lower part of the body upon the couch , they supported the upper part by the left arm upon a cushion , the right hand only being used in taking food:  so , etc.;    c. acc.: mensam, Att. ap.   : : : :   absol., .—Since three persons usually reclined upon such a couch , these expressions arose: in summo , medium and imum adcumbere; and the series began on the left side, since they lay supported by the left arm. The whole arrangement is explained by the following figure:  Among the three lecti, the lectus medius was the most honorable; and on each lectus, the locus medius was more honorable than the summus; and this had the preference to the imus or ultimus. The consul or other magistrate usually sat as imus of the lectus medius , in order that, by his position at the corner, he might be able, without trouble, to attend to any official business that might occur. The place no. 7 seems, for a similar reason, to have been taken by the host. See on this subject Salmas.  Smith's Antiq.; Becker's Gall. 3, p. 206 sq. ; and Orell. excurs. ad . This statement explains the passages in   , etc.;   Sall. Fragm. ap.  .— In mal. part. ,  Men. 3, 2, 11; 5, 9, 82.

fullText: , ĭī, and rarely īvi, ĭtum , 4, v. n. and a. , to go to or approach a person or thing .  Lit.  In gen., constr. Fragm. ap. : : — With in: priusquam Romam atque in horum conventum adiretis, Cic.  Verr. 2, 4, 11, § 26 ed. Halm.—Esp.: adire in jus, to go to law:   , and in the Plebiscit. de Thermens. lin. 42: QVO DE EA RE IN IOVS ADITVM ERIT, cf. Dirks., Versuche S. p. 193.— Absol.: : .— With acc.: : : : : : :  so with latter supine: .—With local adv.: : .— Esp.,  To approach one for the purpose of addressing, asking aid, consulting, and the like, to address, apply to, consult . —Constr. with ad or oftener with acc.; hence also pass.: : : : cum pacem peto, cum placo, cum adeo, et cum appello meam, Lucil. ap. : : .—Pass.: : .—Hence: adire aliquem per epistulam, to address one in writing, by a letter:  and 10; cf.  .—So also: adire deos, aras, deorum sedes, etc., to approach the gods, their altars, etc., as a suppliant : quoi me ostendam? quod templum adeam? Att. ap. : : : : :  cf. : .—  To go to a thing in order to examine it, to visit: : .— To come up to one in a hostile manner, to assail, attack: : : . Fig.  To go to the performance of any act, to enter upon, to undertake, set about, undergo, submit to .—With ad or the acc. : : : : .—With acc.: : :  cf.: : ut vitae periculum aditurus videretur, Auct. B. G. 8, 48: maximos labores et summa pericula. : : : : : .—Hence of an inheritance, t. t., to enter on:  so   and Dig.; .— Adire manum alicui, prov., to deceive one, to make sport of :  so   .

Cortius ad , and ad .—But sometimes adhibere in consilium = admittere in cons., to admit to a consultation. —So trop.: .— Adhibere aliquem cenae, epulis, etc., to invite to a dinner, to a banquet, etc., to entertain:  so   : in convivium, Nep. praef. 7.—And absol., to receive, to treat: : .— Adhibere se ad aliquid, to betake or apply one's self to a thing, i. e. to devote attention to it: ; and absol.: adhibere se, to appear or to behave one's self in any manner: .— Adhibere aliquid ad aliquid, alicui rei, or with in and abl., to put a thing to a determinate use, to apply, to use or employ for or in any thing definite :  cf.  : : : : : : : : : :  and with de: : modum, to set a limit to, to set bounds to: : : cf.  : : .— Adhibere aliquid, in gen., to use, employ, exercise: : : :  : : : .— In later Lat.: alicui aliquem, to bring up, quote one to another as authority for an assertion: .

fullText: , īvi, or ĭi, ītum, 4, v. n., to neigh to or after.  Lit., constr. with dat. and acc., also ad and in with acc.:  cf.  .—Hence, of lewd persons, Plaut. Fragm. ap. Mai. p. 19; Prud. ap. : : : so, — Fig., to strive after or long for with voluptuous desire: admissarius iste ad illius orationem adhinnivit, gave his passionate assent to, expressed his delight in, etc., : .

, āri, ātus, 1, v. dep., to encourage, urge, exhort one to a thing, constr. with ad, in, de, or absol.: : : : : : : .—Absol.: : .—Followed by ut, ne, or the simple subj.: : : : adhortari se, to rouse or bestir one's self: ferus ipse sese adhortans rapidum incitat animo, Catull. 63, 85.!*? , āvi, v. a., to entertain as guest.—Only trop.:

, ēgi, actum, 3, v. a. , to drive, bring, or take a person or thing to a place .—Constr. usu. with ad, but also with acc., dat., in or local adv.  Lit., of cattle (cf. ago, I.: : : : . —Of persons: : : .—Hence: adigere aliquem arbitrum , to compel one to come before an arbiter :  so  .—Of things: : , and absol.: : .—Esp. often of weapons, to drive home, plunge, thrust, to send to a place:  cf.  so  : : : cf. : : .— And from the weapons transf. to the wound, to inflict : : : . In : mare quod adigit ad ostium Rhodani, we have a false reading, for which Nipperdey restored adjacet.

In gen.: :  fin.: :  so :   : .— Esp. In gen.:  : : : : :  cf. : .— Esp.  Of those who admitted one on account of some business; and under the emperors, for the purpose of salutation, to allow one admittance or access, to grant an audience (the t. t. for this; v. admissio, admissionalis;   cf. : : Casino salutatum veniebant;    : : : :  : .—Metaph.: .— Of a harlot:  .—Also of the breeding of animals, to put the male to the female (cf.:    cf.    .—Also used of the female of animals, , and .— Admittere aliquem ad consilium, to admit one to counsel or consultation: :  Halm.—Hence:    .— Of a horse, to let go or run, to give loose reins to : : : :  so  .—Hence of the hair, to let it flow loosely:    Fig.  Of words, entreaties, etc., to permit a thing to come, to give access or grant admittance, to receive:  : .—Hence also absol.:  Gron.; : tunc admitte jocos, give admittance to jesting, i. e. allow it, .—So also: : .— Of an act, event, etc., to let it be done, to allow, permit .—With acc. of thing: : : : .—With subj. clause: .—With acc. and inf.:  so acc. of person alone: .—Hence, in the language of soothsayers, t. t. of birds which give a favorable omen, = addīco, to be propitious, to favor: : .— Of an unlawful act, design, etc., to grant admittance to one's self; hence, become guiliy of, to perpetrate, to commit , often with a reflexive pron., in me, etc. : : : :  :  Müll.: : .—And without such reflexive pron.: :  so, : : : : : : : : : : :  so 2, 37; 3, 59 al.

, mōvi, mōtum, 2, v. a. , to move a person or thing; to bring, conduct, lead, carry, etc., to or toward a place .  Lit.  In gen., constr. with ad or with dat. : dum ne exercitum propius urbem  Romam CC milia admoveret, : :  ext.; so : .—Hence, also, sometimes absol., to draw near, to approach, to bring near: : : . —Trop.: :  : : :  fin.: :  so  : Hannibalem admotum, i. e. adductum altaribus, led or conducted to, : : : : : : : : : : : : : .— Esp. , ui. ultum, 2, v. a. . , āvi, ātum, 1, v. a. , to like, to love,  (both in the higher and the lower sense, opp. odisse; while diligere () designates esteem, regard; opp. neglegere or spernere; cf. Doed. Syn. IV. p. 97; in the high sense in the philos. writings and Epp. of Cicero; often in the low sense, esp. in the comic poets. In the Vulg. amo and amor are comparatively little used, prob. from their bad associations, amo being used 51 times and amor 20. Instead of these words, diligo, dilectio and caritas were used. Diligo occurs 422 times, and dilectio and caritas 144 times in all; dilectio 43 and caritas 101 times).  In gen.: : :  : : : : : : .—So, amare aliquem ex animo, to love with all one's heart, : : : : .—Amare in ccntr. with diligere, as stronger, more affectionate: Clodius valde me diligit, vel, ut  dicam, valde me amat,  :  id. Fragm. ap. ; .—But diligere, as indicative of esteem, is more emph. than amare, which denotes an instinctive or affectionate love: : : : diligis () me plus his? Etiam, Domine, tu scis quia amo () te,  sqq., ubi v. Alford, Gr. Test. al.—Hence in asseverations: ita me dii ament or amabunt, so may the gods love me, by the love of the gods, most assuredly: : : : .—Hence also ellipt.: ita me Juppiter! , .—And as a salutation: Me. Salvus atque fortunatus,  Euclio, semper sies. Eu. Di te ament, Me gadore, the gods bless you! — Esp.  Amare se, of vain men, to be in love with, to be pleased with one's self, also, to be selfish : :  so  : .— Of unlawful love, :  et saep.:  : : :   Heind.;   al. — Trop., to love a thing, to like, to be fond of, to find pleasure in, delight in: : : : : : : : : : : : : amat Janua limen, loves to remain shut, i. e. is constantly closed,  so, —With inf. as object: : .— Amare aliquem de or in aliquā re, quod, etc., to like one for something, to be obliged to one for something, to be under obligation, be thankful.  With de: : .— With in: .— With quod: : amas me, quod te non vidi? Domit. Afer. ap. .—Also without prep. or quod: soror, parce, amabo. Anter. Quiesco. Adelph. Esse often stands without a subject expressed, or with an indef. subj., as antecedent of a rel.-clause, whose verb may be in the indic. or subj.; the former only when the subject is conceived as particular or limited, and actually existing; the latter always when it is conceived as indefinite; cf. Gram. § 365; but the distinctions usually drawn by grammarians are not always observed by the best writers; and the subjunctive is always admissible, being the prevailing construction after sunt qui in class. prose, and nearly universal in postAug. writers: sunt, qui , there are those who , or simply some.
